6:The Jacobian is built as the Albanese object of $C$ in the category of smooth proper group schemes over $k$, and the construction stratifies by genus. For positive genus the witness \emph{object} is the abelian variety $\Pic^0_{C/k}$ produced by \textbf{Route~A (the Picard scheme via FGA representability)}: this is the project's committed critical path, and it is \emph{mandatory} for the positive-genus object regardless of any other route choice --- the object must be a genuine $g$-dimensional abelian variety even when $C(k) = \emptyset$ (see \cref{thm:nonempty_jacobianWitness} Route~A and \cref{def:positiveGenusWitness}). The FGA representability for $\Pic_{C/k}$ and its Hilbert/Quot prerequisites are the single largest Mathlib build-out the project gates on. For genus $0$ the witness object is instead the trivial scheme $\Spec k$, \textbf{decoupled} from Route~A's representability engine; the only remaining content in that arm is a rigidity \emph{statement} (\cref{thm:rigidity_over_kbar}), whose committed proof route is the characteristic-free theorem-of-the-cube $\to$ rigidity-lemma chain of \cref{sec:av_rigidity_route_c}, \emph{not} the differential / Serre-duality argument.
397:        \item[\textbf{(c) [committed; characteristic-free]}] \emph{Theorem of the cube $\to$ rigidity lemma.} $\mathbb P^1_{\bar k}$ is a nonsingular, unirational (indeed rational) variety, so every rational map $\mathbb P^1_{\bar k} \dashrightarrow A$ to an abelian variety is constant by \cref{prop:unirational_to_AV_constant} (Milne, \emph{Abelian Varieties}, Proposition~3.10); a morphism is in particular a rational map, so $f$ is constant. The cited proposition rests on \cref{lem:rational_map_to_AV_extends} (Theorem~3.2: a rational map from a nonsingular variety to an abelian variety is everywhere defined), \cref{cor:complete_product_to_AV_decomp} (Corollary~1.5), \cref{lem:rigidity_theorem} (the Rigidity Theorem~1.1), and \cref{thm:theorem_of_the_cube} (the theorem of the cube). This chain uses \emph{neither} $H^0(C, \Omega_C) = 0$ / Serre duality \emph{nor} the Picard representability engine, and is valid in arbitrary characteristic. It is the route the project commits to for \cref{thm:rigidity_over_kbar}; see \cref{sec:av_rigidity_route_c}.
417:      \item[\textbf{(C.2.g)}] \emph{Mathlib gap statement.} The keystone fact of Sub-step~C.2.d --- that every morphism from a smooth proper geometrically irreducible genus-$0$ curve over an algebraically closed field $\bar k$ to a positive-dimensional smooth proper geometrically irreducible group scheme over $\bar k$ is constant --- is \emph{not} present in current Mathlib (snapshot \texttt{b80f227}) in any form usable here. The project records it as the named declaration \cref{thm:rigidity_over_kbar} of \cref{chap:RigidityKbar}, whose base field currently carries $[\mathtt{IsAlgClosed}\ \bar k]$ and (pending the characteristic-free route below) $[\mathtt{CharZero}\ \bar k]$. The \textbf{committed} proof route for this declaration is route~(c) of C.2.d: the theorem-of-the-cube $\to$ rigidity-lemma chain (\cref{sec:av_rigidity_route_c}, headline \cref{prop:unirational_to_AV_constant}), which is characteristic-free and uses neither Serre duality nor the Picard engine, and which --- once formalised --- lets the $[\mathtt{CharZero}\ \bar k]$ hypothesis be dropped. The differential decomposition into the shared cotangent-vanishing pile of \cref{sec:RigidityKbar_shared_pile} pieces (i)--(iii) --- (i) cotangent triviality of a group scheme over $\bar k$ via the functorial shear iso; (ii) scheme-level $\mathrm d f = 0 \Rightarrow$ $f$ factors through $\Spec \bar k$ via the \texttt{Differential.ContainConstants} typeclass plus the iter-125-refactored \texttt{Scheme.Over.ext\_of\_eqOnOpen}; (iii) characteristic-$p$ handling via the intrinsic absolute Frobenius $F_X$ --- is the \textbf{fallback} route~(a), off the critical path but retained in the tree (each piece an upstream Mathlib gap-fill in its own right; see \cref{chap:RigidityKbar}). When $g = \dim A = 0$ the statement is vacuous and the declaration's conclusion is automatic. The reduction step C.2.b reuses the project's already-formalised Theorem~\ref{thm:GrpObj_eq_of_eqOnOpen} (after the iter-125 refactor, this is \texttt{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.Over.ext\_of\_eqOnOpen}, stated at the scheme level: source reduced and geometrically irreducible, target separated); the promotion step C.2.e uses standard reduced-source / separated-target lemmas, partially in Mathlib. The descent step C.2.f --- from $\bar k$ back to the base field $k$ --- is \emph{not} a Mathlib gap: it is a short ($\sim 2$-line) consequence of \texttt{AlgebraicGeometry.Flat.epi\_of\_flat\_of\_surjective} (already in Mathlib, in \texttt{Mathlib.AlgebraicGeometry.Morphisms.Flat}) together with base-change-square commutativity, and is cheaper than the proper-cohomology flat-base-change machinery a cohomological descent would have required.
434:    \item[\textbf{($\gamma$)}] \emph{The rigidity statement for morphisms from a smooth proper geometrically irreducible genus-$0$ curve to a smooth proper geometrically irreducible group scheme, over an algebraically closed field $\bar k$.} The genus-$0$ arm needs \emph{only} this rigidity \emph{statement}, \textbf{decoupled} from both the cotangent-vanishing pile and the Picard representability of ($\alpha$): its witness object is the trivial $\Spec k$, and the statement is the project's named declaration \cref{thm:rigidity_over_kbar} (\cref{chap:RigidityKbar}), currently carrying $[\mathtt{IsAlgClosed}\ \bar k]$ (and, pending the route below, $[\mathtt{CharZero}\ \bar k]$). The \textbf{committed} proof route is the characteristic-free theorem-of-the-cube $\to$ rigidity-lemma chain of \cref{sec:av_rigidity_route_c} (route~(c): headline \cref{prop:unirational_to_AV_constant} = Milne Proposition~3.10), which uses neither Serre duality nor representability. The differential decomposition into the shared cotangent-vanishing pile pieces (i)+(ii)+(iii) of \cref{sec:RigidityKbar_shared_pile} --- cotangent triviality of a group scheme over $\bar k$ via the functorial shear iso; scheme-level $\mathrm d f = 0 \Rightarrow$ $f$ factors through $\Spec \bar k$ via the \texttt{Differential.ContainConstants} typeclass; characteristic-$p$ handling via the intrinsic absolute Frobenius $F_X$ --- is the \textbf{fallback} route~(a), off the critical path but retained in the tree. The genus-$0$ arm of the witness existence is packaged as \cref{def:genusZeroWitness} (\texttt{AlgebraicGeometry.genusZeroWitness}), which over a general base field $k$ \emph{descends} the over-$\bar k$ rigidity conclusion to $k$: for each $k$-rational marked point $P \in C(k)$ it base-changes the data $(C, A, f, P)$ along $\Spec \bar k \to \Spec k$ (genus is stable under base change for a geometrically irreducible curve, so $C_{\bar k}$ is again a genus-$0$ curve), applies \cref{thm:rigidity_over_kbar} over $\bar k$ to conclude $f_{\bar k}$ is constant, then descends the morphism equality back to $k$ along the faithfully-flat surjection $\Spec \bar k \to \Spec k$ (Sub-step~C.2.f, via \texttt{AlgebraicGeometry.Flat.epi\_of\_flat\_of\_surjective}). The $C(k) = \emptyset$ branch is vacuously true (Brauer--Severi conics over $\mathbb Q$). Independently of ($\alpha$), establishing ($\gamma$) together with the short descent step lets the genus-$0$ part of the witness be discharged unconditionally via \cref{def:genusZeroWitness}; the higher-genus part is packaged as \cref{def:positiveGenusWitness} (\texttt{AlgebraicGeometry.positiveGenusWitness}, iter-134 scaffold) whose body closure is gated on Route A ($\alpha$). Per the iter-135 body restructure of \cref{thm:nonempty_jacobianWitness}, the witness existence is now a case-split $\mathtt{by\_cases}\ h : \genus\,C = 0$ delegating to \cref{def:genusZeroWitness} and \cref{def:positiveGenusWitness} respectively, converting the formerly inline \texttt{sorry} into honest delegation to the two named scaffolds.
446:The genus-$0$ sub-case of \cref{thm:nonempty_jacobianWitness} admits an explicit witness construction at the Lean level, packaged separately from the general existence statement so that the genus-$0$ branch can be discharged \emph{independently of Route~A}. Its witness object is the trivial scheme $\Spec k$; the only remaining mathematical content is the rigidity statement \cref{thm:rigidity_over_kbar}, whose committed proof route is the characteristic-free AV-rigidity lemma of \cref{sec:av_rigidity_route_c} (route~(c)), \emph{not} the differential / Serre-duality route and \emph{not} the Picard representability engine.
449:\label{sec:av_rigidity_route_c}
451:The genus-$0$ witness \emph{object} is the trivial scheme $\Spec k$; the only remaining mathematical content of the genus-$0$ arm is the rigidity \emph{statement} \cref{thm:rigidity_over_kbar}. The project commits to proving it by the characteristic-free \emph{theorem-of-the-cube $\to$ rigidity-lemma} chain of Milne, \emph{Abelian Varieties}, recorded in the blocks below. The headline fact the genus-$0$ arm consumes is \cref{prop:rigidity_genus0_curve_to_AV}, the specialisation to a genus-$0$ curve of \cref{prop:unirational_to_AV_constant} (Milne, Proposition~3.10), applied to $\mathbb P^1_{\bar k}$ (a rational, hence unirational, variety). This chain uses \emph{neither} $H^0(C, \Omega_C) = 0$ / Serre duality \emph{nor} the FGA $\Pic$ representability engine, so the genus-$0$ arm is fully \textbf{decoupled} from Route~A. The same rigidity machinery is what the positive-genus Albanese universal property (Milne, Propositions~6.1/6.4) needs anyway, here used independently of the Picard representability.
455:  \label{thm:theorem_of_the_cube}
471:  \label{lem:rigidity_theorem}
502:  \uses{thm:theorem_of_the_cube}
507:  \uses{lem:rigidity_theorem}
513:  \label{cor:complete_product_to_AV_decomp}
527:  \uses{lem:rigidity_theorem}
528:  Let $V$, $W$ be complete varieties over $k$ with $k$-rational points $v_0$, $w_0$, with projections $p \colon V \times W \to V$, $q \colon V \times W \to W$, and let $A$ be an abelian variety. Every morphism $h \colon V \times W \to A$ with $h(v_0, w_0) = 0$ decomposes uniquely as $h = f \circ p + g \circ q$ with $f \colon V \to A$, $g \colon W \to A$ satisfying $f(v_0) = 0$ and $g(w_0) = 0$. The decomposition follows by applying \cref{lem:rigidity_theorem} to $h - f\circ p - g\circ q$, which kills both coordinate axes.
533:  \label{lem:rational_map_to_AV_extends}
549:  \label{prop:unirational_to_AV_constant}
568:  \uses{lem:rational_map_to_AV_extends, cor:complete_product_to_AV_decomp}
573:  \uses{prop:unirational_to_AV_constant, cor:complete_product_to_AV_decomp, lem:rational_map_to_AV_extends}
574:  We may assume $k$ algebraically closed. The dominating rational map $\mathbb A^n \dashrightarrow V$ composed with $\alpha$ extends (by \cref{lem:rational_map_to_AV_extends}, after compactifying each factor) to a morphism $\beta \colon \mathbb P^1 \times \cdots \times \mathbb P^1 \to A$. An induction starting from \cref{cor:complete_product_to_AV_decomp} writes $\beta(x_1, \ldots, x_d) = \sum_i \beta_i(x_i)$ for regular maps $\beta_i \colon \mathbb P^1 \to A$; the one-factor case (a morphism $\mathbb P^1 \to A$, killed by the Rigidity Theorem applied to its difference of values) shows each $\beta_i$ is constant, hence $\beta$, hence $\alpha$, is constant.
579:  \label{prop:rigidity_genus0_curve_to_AV}
585:  \uses{prop:unirational_to_AV_constant, lem:rational_map_to_AV_extends}
590:  \uses{prop:unirational_to_AV_constant, lem:rational_map_to_AV_extends, prop:rigidity_genus0_curve_to_AV}
591:  Over the algebraically closed field $\bar k$, a smooth proper geometrically irreducible genus-$0$ curve has a $\bar k$-rational point and is therefore isomorphic to $\mathbb P^1_{\bar k}$, which is a rational --- hence unirational --- nonsingular variety. The morphism $f$ is in particular a rational map $\mathbb P^1_{\bar k} \dashrightarrow A$, so \cref{prop:unirational_to_AV_constant} (Milne, Proposition~3.10) shows $f$ is constant; \cref{lem:rational_map_to_AV_extends} guarantees that there is no indeterminacy to worry about (the rational map is everywhere defined). The pointed hypothesis $f(p) = \eta_A$ pins the constant value to $\eta_A$, so $f$ equals the constant morphism at $\eta_A$. The argument invokes no differential ($df = 0$) input, no $H^0(C, \Omega_C) = 0$ / Serre duality, and no Picard representability, and is valid in arbitrary characteristic --- once formalised it lets the $[\mathtt{CharZero}\ \bar k]$ hypothesis currently carried by \cref{thm:rigidity_over_kbar} be dropped.
616:  For the universal factorisation: given a smooth proper geometrically irreducible group scheme $A$ over $k$ with identity element $\eta_A \colon \mathbf{1} \to A$ and a morphism $f \colon C \to A$ with $P \circ f = \eta_A$, we must exhibit a unique morphism $g \colon J \to A$ such that $f = \alpha \circ g$. \emph{Existence}: take $g := \eta_A \colon \mathbf{1} \to A$. Then $\alpha \circ g = \mathtt{toUnit}\,C \circ \eta_A$, which equals $f$ precisely when $f$ is the constant morphism at $\eta_A$. We obtain this equality by descent from the algebraic closure $\bar k = \mathrm{AlgebraicClosure}\,k$. Base-change the data along $\Spec \bar k \to \Spec k$: the curve $C_{\bar k}$ is again smooth proper geometrically irreducible of genus $0$ (genus is stable under base change for a geometrically irreducible curve), the group scheme $A_{\bar k}$ is again smooth proper geometrically irreducible, the base-changed point $P_{\bar k}$ is a $\bar k$-rational point, and $f_{\bar k}$ still kills it: $f_{\bar k}(P_{\bar k}) = \eta_{A_{\bar k}}$. By \cref{thm:rigidity_over_kbar} (the project's named rigidity declaration of \cref{chap:RigidityKbar}, currently carrying $[\mathtt{IsAlgClosed}\ \bar k]$ and $[\mathtt{CharZero}\ \bar k]$, the latter removable once the characteristic-free route~(c) of \cref{sec:av_rigidity_route_c} is formalised), $f_{\bar k}$ equals the constant morphism $\mathtt{toUnit}\,C_{\bar k} \circ \eta_{A_{\bar k}}$ over $\bar k$. Finally we descend this morphism equality back to $k$: the projection $p \colon C_{\bar k} \to C$ is the base change of the faithfully-flat surjection $\Spec \bar k \to \Spec k$, hence faithfully flat and surjective, hence an epimorphism of schemes by \texttt{AlgebraicGeometry.Flat.epi\_of\_flat\_of\_surjective}; right-cancelling $p$ against the base-change-square identities yields $f = \mathtt{toUnit}\,C \circ \eta_A$ as $k$-scheme morphisms (Sub-step~C.2.f of \cref{thm:nonempty_jacobianWitness}). \emph{Uniqueness}: any two morphisms $\mathbf{1} \to A$ in $\mathrm{Over}\,(\Spec k)$ agreeing on $P \circ (-) = \eta_A$ are equal by the universal property of the terminal object $\mathbf{1}$ in $\mathrm{Over}\,(\Spec k)$ as a category (a morphism out of $\mathbf{1}$ in $\mathrm{Over}\,(\Spec k)$ is determined by where it sends the unique generator, here pinned to $\eta_A$).
659:  \paragraph{Body closure status.} The Lean body of \texttt{AlgebraicGeometry.genusZeroWitness} (in \texttt{AlgebraicJacobian/Jacobian.lean}) is currently \texttt{sorry}; the closure is gated on the body of \cref{thm:rigidity_over_kbar} (M2.a), whose \textbf{committed} proof route is route~(c) --- the characteristic-free theorem-of-the-cube $\to$ rigidity-lemma chain of \cref{sec:av_rigidity_route_c} (headline \cref{prop:rigidity_genus0_curve_to_AV}), which is decoupled from both Route~A representability and Serre duality. The differential decomposition into pieces (i)+(ii)+(iii) of the shared cotangent-vanishing pile (\cref{sec:RigidityKbar_shared_pile}) is the retained \emph{fallback} route~(a), off the critical path. (The chart-algebra envelope of the fallback supplies only the converse implication $df = 0 \Rightarrow$ constant, and carries a characteristic-$p$ gap; the committed route~(c) avoids that gap entirely.)
701:  \item \textbf{Layer I --- direct definition.} The Jacobian of $C$ is defined uniformly as the underlying scheme of the Albanese witness provided by Theorem~\ref{thm:nonempty_jacobianWitness}, carrying the four properties of Theorems~\ref{thm:Jacobian_grpObj}--\ref{thm:Jacobian_geomIrred} (each obtained by projection from the witness). The genus-$0$ case is included: the witness object is the trivial $\Spec k$, and the witness's universal property carries only the rigidity \emph{statement} for morphisms from a smooth proper geometrically irreducible genus-$0$ curve to a smooth proper geometrically irreducible group scheme --- \textbf{decoupled} from the Picard representability of Route~A. This rigidity is established over the algebraic closure $\bar k = \mathrm{AlgebraicClosure}\,k$ via the named declaration \cref{thm:rigidity_over_kbar} of \cref{chap:RigidityKbar} (carrying $[\mathtt{IsAlgClosed}\ \bar k]$), whose \textbf{committed} proof route is the characteristic-free theorem-of-the-cube $\to$ rigidity-lemma chain of \cref{sec:av_rigidity_route_c} (route~(c)), \emph{not} the differential / Serre-duality route; the shared cotangent-vanishing pile pieces (i)+(ii)+(iii) are the retained fallback~(a). The conclusion over a general base field $k$ is then obtained by \emph{descending} the over-$\bar k$ morphism equality along the faithfully-flat surjection $\Spec \bar k \to \Spec k$ (a short consequence of \texttt{AlgebraicGeometry.Flat.epi\_of\_flat\_of\_surjective}). The genus-$0$ arm is packaged as the explicit Lean construction \cref{def:genusZeroWitness}: the underlying scheme is the terminal object $\Spec k$, the universal morphism in the $C(k) \neq \emptyset$ branch is the unique terminal map \texttt{toUnit}\,$C$, and the universal factorisation reduces to \cref{thm:rigidity_over_kbar} over $\bar k$ followed by descent to $k$.

